In this article, it is announced that January is National Slavery and Human Trafficking Prevention Month in the United States. The article discusses the history of slavery in the US, including its abolition through the Emancipation Proclamation and the 13th Amendment. It also acknowledges that slavery still exists today, both globally and within the US, and calls for action to combat human trafficking. The article emphasizes the need for collaboration between various agencies, organizations, and individuals to protect victims and prosecute traffickers. It urges Americans to educate themselves about modern slavery and observe the month with appropriate programs and activities. The article concludes with a proclamation by President Barack Obama, officially declaring January 2010 as National Slavery and Human Trafficking Prevention Month.